Therefore the interpretation of the dose-response relationship is based on certain assumptions:


the response is proportional to the concentration at the target site;

the concentration at the target site is related to the dose;

the response is causally related to the compound administered.

The concentration of a chemical in the blood plasma and its change over time (Figure 2.8) is a reflection of the absorption, distribution, metabolism and excretion of the chemical. For example, after a drug is taken orally, the plasma level profile will be different from the profile of a drug given intravenously (Figure 2.9). The plasma level of a chemical and its change over time are vitally important pieces of information for a toxicologist. This is because:


it reflects the concentration of the chemical in the tissues more readily than does the dose of the chemical which may be incompletely absorbed;

it may reflect the concentration of the chemical at the target site;

it is necessary in order to calculate parameters such as half-life, VD, AUC and body burden;

it may indicate the type of distribution which the compound is undergoing (i.e. which compartments it is distributed to);

the plasma level when plotted against time gives an indication of the duration of significant exposure (area under the curve or AUC; see Figure 2.8).

Biliary excretion, therefore, may:


increase the half-life of the compound;

lead to the production of toxic metabolites in the gastrointestinal tract;

increase hepatic exposure via the enterohepatic recirculation;

be saturated and lead to hepatic damage.

Therefore, in summary, metabolism leads to:


transformation of the molecule into a more polar metabolite;

possible increase in molecular weight and size;

facilitation of excretion and so elimination from the organism.

The consequences of these changes are:


the half-life of the compound is decreased;

the exposure time is shortened;

the possibility of accumulation is reduced;

a probable change in biological activity;

a change in the duration of the biological activity.

The site and route of absorption is important from two points of view:


the route may influence the eventual systemic toxicity as already indicated in Chapter 2;

the site may be important if there is local toxicity at the point of absorption.

The basic mechanisms underlying these types of toxicity may also be summarized:


direct and predictable toxic effects due to altered or inhibited metabolism and occurring after overdoses;

toxic effects occurring after repeated therapeutic doses with a metabolic, pharmacological or maybe immunological basis;

direct but unpredictable toxic effects occurring after single therapeutic doses and due to idiosyncratic metabolism or a pharmacodynamic response;

toxic effects due to another drug or substance interfering with the disposition or pharmacological response of the drug in question.

The predisposing factors so far recognized in halothane hepatotoxicity are:


multiple exposures, which seem to sensitize the patient to future exposures;

sex, females being more commonly affected than males in the ratio 1.8:1;

obesity, 68 per cent of patients in one study were obese;

allergy, a previous history of allergy was found in one third of patients.

Exposure to asbestos via inhalation can lead to the following conditions:


Asbestosis or interstitial fibrosis of the lung;

Benign pleural disease;

Bronchial carcinoma;

Malignant mesothelioma.

The toxicity of a chemical can be determined in one of three ways:


by observing human (or animal or plant) populations exposed to a chemical (epidemiology);

by administering the chemical to animals or plants under controlled conditions and observing the effects (in vivo);

by exposing cells, subcellular fractions or single-celled organisms to the chemical (in vitro).

Risk assessment would be carried out on chemicals for the following reasons:


the chemical is likely to be a hazard to humans in the environment;

the likelihood of persistence of the chemical in the environment and bioaccumulation;

the likelihood that sensitive human and ecological populations may be exposed to significant levels;

indication of hazard to human health;

174likelihood of exposure via use or production.

The modifying or safety factors are as follows:


10× for human variability (intra species);

10× for extrapolation from animals to humans (interspecies variability);

10× if less than chronic doses have been used;

10× if the LOAEL rather than the NOAEL is used;

0.1–10× modifying factor. This is only used for determination of the RfD (EPA).
